<li id="cite_note-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFAllen2003" class="citation web cs1"><a href="/wiki/John_L._Allen_Jr." title="John L. Allen Jr.">Allen, John L.</a> (15 August 2003). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://nationalcatholicreporter.org/word/word0815.htm">"Explaining "Crimen Sollicitationis"<span class="cs1-kern-right"></span>"</a>. National Catholic Reporter<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">26 March</span> 2010</span>. <q>It allows witnesses to speak freely, accused priests to protect their good name until guilt is established, and victims to come forward who don't want publicity. Such secrecy is also not unique to sex abuse. It applies, for example, to the appointment of bishops.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Explaining+%22Crimen+Sollicitationis%22&amp;rft.pub=National+Catholic+Reporter&amp;rft.date=2003-08-15&amp;rft.aulast=Allen&amp;rft.aufirst=John+L.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fnationalcatholicreporter.org%2Fword%2Fword0815.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACrimen+sollicitationis" class="Z3988"></span></span>
